<a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/16/opinion/sunday/where-are-the-people-of-color-in-childrens-books.html?_r=1\" title=\"\">article for the New York Times</a> at the weekend. \"Books transmit values. They explore our common humanity. What is the message when some children are not represented in those books?\" he asked. \"Where are black children going to get a sense of who they are and what they can be? … I'm told that black children, and boys in particular, don't read. Small wonder. There is work to be done.\"</p><p></p><p>Myers was pointing to <a href=\"http://ccbc.education.wisc.edu/books/pcstats.asp\" title=\"\">research done by the Cooperative Children's Book Centre</a> at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, which has counted the number of children's books featuring people of colour since 1985. Ten years ago, of 3,200 books received by the centre, 171 were about black people, 95 about American Indians, 78 about Asians and 63 about Latinos. Last year, these numbers had fallen, with 93 of 3,200 books about black people, 34 about American Indians, 69 about Asians and 57 about Latinos.</p><p></p><p>Myers's article, backed up by a piece from his son and fellow author Christopher Myers on the <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/16/opinion/sunday/the-apartheid-of-childrens-literature.html?smid=tw-share\" title=\"\">\"apartheid of children's literature\"</a>, prompted the bestselling novelist Jennifer Weiner to launch a call to \"tweet your favourite books with non-white characters using #colormyshelf. Let's build a list. Then: let's go shopping.\"</p><p></p><p>\"Your kid's/school's/library's shelf doesn't look like America,\" wrote Weiner on Twitter. \"If publishers see a market for books with non-white main characters, they'll give us more.\" She was inundated with suggestions, from titles by Sherman Alexie and Malorie Blackman to Myers himself, with readers and authors also sending her lists from <a href=\"http://www.forharriet.com/2013/10/25-empowering-books-for-little-black.html\" title=\"\">\"25 Empowering Books for Little Black Girls\"</a> to 30 \"outstanding\" books <a href=\"http://www.slj.com/2013/11/collection-development/focus-on-collection-development/resources-and-kid-lit-about-american-indians-focus-on/\" title=\"\">about American Indians</a>.</p><p></p><p>There are no similar statistics about the situation in the UK, but Beth Cox, who works for the collective on children's books and diversity, <a href=\"http://www.inclusiveminds.com/\" title=\"\">Inclusive Minds</a>, said the lack of people of colour in children's books in the UK is \"still a huge problem\".</p><p></p><p>\"There seems to be a huge fear of putting black people on book covers and/or marketing books with black covers to anyone who isn't black,\" she added.</p><p></p><p>Verna Wilkins established children's publisher <a href=\"http://www.tamarindbooks.co.uk/aboutus.asp\" title=\"\">Tamarind Books</a> in the UK in 1987 to address the lack of diversity in children's publishing in the UK. In <a href=\"http://www.tamarindbooks.co.uk/downloads/tamarind_righttobeseen.pdf\" title=\"\">a 2008 lecture</a>, she explained that she was moved to launch the publisher when her son came home from school with a booklet, on which he had coloured a picture of himself in pink. She offered him a brown crayon to fix it. \"It has to be that colour. It's for a book!\" he told her.\"I had no choice. I had to become a publisher,\" said Wilkins.</p><p></p><p>Today, Tamarind is part of Penguin Random House, and picture book editor Joe Marriott said that \"there's still work to be done\" in terms of diversity in children's books.</p><p></p><p>\"On the Tamarind list we actively look for inclusive stories with characters from varied cultural backgrounds and we've published some wonderful books over the years, both picture books such as The Silence Seeker or Mum's Late, and more recently books for older children such as Jamila Gavin's Blackberry Blue or Crystal Chan's debut Bird,\" he said, adding that in the company more widely, \"half of the debut novels we're publishing this year feature black, Asian or mixed-race main characters\", from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/15/running-girl-garvie-smith-mystery-simon-mason\" title=\"\">Simon Mason's Running Girl</a>, which has a black teenage boy protagonist, to My Mummy is Magic, \"a lovely picture book for Mother's Day which just happens to depict a mixed-race family\".</p><p></p><p>\"In each of these titles, the diversity is unselfconscious. It is so important for all children to feel represented in the books they read, in a way that doesn't feel forced or as though ethnicities are pigeonholed – publishing and promoting inclusive books is something to which we're utterly committed,\" said Marriott.</p><p></p><p>Cox agreed, stressing the importance of increasing \"the number of books relevant to cultural and racial diversity, including positive representation of Asian as well as black families\".</p><p></p><p>\"All children have the right to be included in books, to see faces that they can relate to on the covers, to meet characters with similar families, lives and experiences, and that is one of the reasons that we established Inclusive Minds. &nbsp;Equally important is for children to see&nbsp;difference in books, to learn about those who are different from themselves, and to realise that they do, in fact, have many similarities,\" said Cox.</p><p></p><p>\"Discussions about diversity in books&nbsp;are often focused exclusively on&nbsp;cultural or racial diversity, but we believe it's important to&nbsp;address&nbsp;all areas of diversity as there are so many children who aren't able to find themselves in books. Publishers are starting to become aware of this, but unfortunately stereotypes are still perpetuated, and inclusion is often forced. Our aim is to work with the publishers in order to help them develop fully-rounded characters and to make their books naturally inclusive.\"</p>","headline":"Diversity in children's books: colouring in required","trailText":"There are growing calls for young people's reading to broaden its picture of society from what is currently a depressingly monochrome view","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/20/1395314847904/Young-black-boy-007.jpg","wordcount":"858","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-27T11:19:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/20/diversity-children-books-colour-young-people","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/20/diversity-children-books-colour-young-people","tags":[{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"books/publishing","webTitle":"Publishing","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/publishing","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/publishing","references":[]},{"id":"profile/alisonflood","webTitle":"Alison Flood","r2ContributorId":"27440","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/3/14/1300117336779/Alison.jpg","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Alison Flood is a writer on guardian.co.uk/books and former news editor of The Bookseller</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/alisonflood","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/profile/alisonflood","references":[]},{"id":"tone/features","webTitle":"Features","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardi