ges. The text is interspersed with cute graphics – charts, tables, maps – that allow you to compare and&nbsp;contrast: a table showing, say, the different ingredients that go into the <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/food/mirepoix\" title=\"\">mirepoix</a> or <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/aug/05/chicken-sofrito-smoked-corn-recipes\" title=\"\">sofrito</a> of various cooking cultures; a simplified map of the spice routes; a table of different chillis; a graphic of the Americas showing how influences (and ingredients) poured in from all sides like troops advancing on a battlefield map.</p><p>Her regions are Europe, the Middle East, Asia, Africa and the Americas. No&nbsp;prawns on the barbie, then. Europe gets the most attention: she looks at four cuisines for each of France (Normandy, Loire Valley, Lyon and Provence) and Spain (Catalonia, northern Spain, central Spain and Andalucia) and five for Italy (Lazio, Emilia-Romagna, Calabria, Sicily, Veneto). China is represented by only Cantonese and Sichuanese cooking, and the whole of Africa gets only three: Ethiopia, west Africa and Morocco (which overlaps a bit with the Middle East in any case). Still, it's unreasonable to expect this book to be able to offer much more than what its author endearingly describes as \"a scant slice of a deep and&nbsp;nuanced pie\".</p><p>Digging about in this deep and nuanced pie (may all our pies be deep&nbsp;and nuanced!), Holland is a resoundingly enthusiastic guide. She always has a kind word for the meekest of ingredients – \"the humble sesame seed\", \"the humble soybean\" and even \"the humble lettuce leaf\". Most of the chapters come enhanced with quotes from an expert in the cuisine – either a&nbsp;local, a food writer or a restaurateur; and with an epigraph from a literary production of some sort. That rounds it&nbsp;out pleasantly. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/jhumpa-lahiri\" title=\"\">Jhumpa Lahiri</a> is quoted in the section on northern India; <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/arundhatiroy\" title=\"\">Arundhati Roy</a> on the south. Korea brings forth references to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/psy\" title=\"\">Psy</a> and <a href=\"http://nothingtoenvy.com/\" title=\"\">Barbara Demick</a>. On German sausages Holland quotes an excellent HL Mencken passage: \"They run in size from little fellows so small and pale and fragile that it seems a crime to eat&nbsp;them, to vast and formidable pieces that look like shells for heavy artillery. And they run in flavour from the most delicate to the most raucous, and in texture from that of feathers caught in&nbsp;a cobweb to that of linoleum.\"</p><p>When we're in Turkey, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/orhanpamuk\" title=\"\">Orhan Pamuk</a>'s remark that \"colour is the touch of the eye, music to the deaf, a&nbsp;word out of the darkness\" sparks a little cadenza on Istanbul's \"wonderful racket of visual splendour … the breathtaking interior of the Blue Mosque, the Bosphorus shimmering at&nbsp;sunset and the coloured glass lamps that create multi-hued silhouettes on the walls of the Grand Bazaar … the mountains of dried fruits and nuts, and piles of brightly coloured spice dusts\".</p><p>Where she's visited, or even lived in, the places she's writing about, Holland puts in welcome splashes of autobiographical colour – though she stops short of giving us a chapter on the distinctive cuisine of Streatham. Some&nbsp;of these recipes are her family's. As a&nbsp;young woman in Madrid, she says, she was thwarted only in being unable to find \"good hummus and my bra size\"; we meet her friend Sophie, \"haunted by artichokes as a&nbsp;teenager\"; hear of an 11-day bike trip&nbsp;from London to Berlin (\"a mad undertaking but we did it\"); recall her arrival in California with \"one suitcase and a volume of Joan Didion's collected writing\" meet the sweary grandpa who retired to Thailand; and so on.</p><p>Intriguing little facts are scattered hither and yon. I didn't know, for instance, that yoghurt was a Turkish invention, about the travels of salt cod,&nbsp;the Iranian/Indian biriani/pilau connection, or about the contested etymology of the Vietnamese soup pho&nbsp;(possibly from the French <em>pot au feu</em>). I&nbsp;enjoyed the whimsical taxonomy of chillis – \"names that could be members of a drug cartel: guajillo, piquin, cascabel, pasilla, anch, mulato, habanero, jalapeno and chipotle\" – and the scholarly footnote on films about noodles: in addition to 2006's <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0780167/\" title=\"\"><em>Udon</em></a>, \"other movies with noodle-based narratives include 2008's <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0806165/\" title=\"\"><em>The Ramen Girl</em></a>, in which Brittany Murphy trains to become a ramen chef, and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/80951/tampopo\" title=\"\"><em>Tampopo</em></a> (1985), set in a family-run noodle shop and dubbed the first 'ramen western'\".</p><p>Holland is also prepared to admit that some of the things people eat will&nbsp;sound pretty fricking disgusting to&nbsp;those of us who don't have the omnivorousness of an <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/anthonybourdain\" title=\"\">Anthony Bourdain</a>. \"Pajata,\" she admits in her chapter on Lazio, \"is not for the faint hearted; resembling a cheese sausage, this is an unweaned calf's intestine filled with milk chyme (its mother's milk, undigested)\". Jeepers. Can't say Korea's soondae (\"a membrane of pig intestine stuffed with pork blood and cellophane noodles\") appeals much either. Still, we can and should admire those whose appetites are more robust, following the proverbial Cantonese principle that \"anything that walks, swims, crawls or flies with its back to heaven is edible\".</p><p>To me, the most appealing aspect of&nbsp;the book is its practical emphasis on&nbsp;cooking these cuisines at home. There are recipes for two or three representative dishes, usually simple and almost always delicious-sounding, at the end of each chapter. For each cuisine Holland supplies a \"larder list\" of key ingredients that stands as an&nbsp;almost poetic shorthand for the flavours. Germany, for instance, asks&nbsp;for: \"Cabbage (red and white), sausages, potatoes, wild mushrooms, rye and pumpernickel breads, mustard, horseradish, caraway, chives, thyme, juniper berries, star anise, cardamom, cinnamon and clove for puddings.\" Holland even gives you, at the beginning, a list of essential kitchen equipment. It's probably not vital to be advised that a&nbsp;corkscrew and a kitchen radio are nice to have, but it's companionable.</p><p>Most importantly, <em>The Edible Atlas</em> makes you hungry. The epigraph to one chapter is a Japanese proverb: \"I'd rather have dumplings than flowers.\" Me too.</p>","headline":"The Edible Atlas: Around the World in 39 Cuisines – review","trailText":"<p>Fancy a bite of pajata or soondae? <strong>Sam Leith</strong> tucks in to Mina Holland's companionable guide to global gastronomy</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/19/1395245214729/apple-pie-004.jpg","wordcount":"1061","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-05-02T14:58:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/20/edible-atlas-around-world-cuisines-review","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/20/edible-atlas-around-world-cuisines-review","tags":[{"id":"books/food","webTitle":"Food and drink","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/food","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/food","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"books/travel-writing","webTitle":"Trav