d in 1955. Photograph: Haywood Magee/Getty Images","width":"368"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-432471769","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/19/1395228757621/JRR-Tolkien-1955-008.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"Haywood Magee","altText":"JRR Tolkien 1955","height":"84","credit":"Haywood Magee/Getty Images","caption":"JRR Tolkien at Oxford in 1955. Photograph: Haywood Magee/Getty Images","width":"140"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/19/1395228765361/JRR-Tolkien-1955-014.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"Haywood Magee","altText":"JRR Tolkien 1955","height":"372","credit":"Haywood Magee/Getty Images","caption":"JRR Tolkien at Oxford in 1955. Photograph: Haywood Magee/Getty Images","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Roy Jenkins: A Well-Rounded Life – review","webPublicationDate":"2014-03-19T07:30:00Z","sectionName":"Books","sectionId":"books","id":"books/2014/mar/19/roy-jenkins-well-rounded-life-alan-johnson-review","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3njjc","standfirst":"Alan Johnson on the achievements, sex life and 'elitism' of a political heavyweight","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>At the farewell dinner given to Roy Jenkins by his closest friends prior to his departure for Brussels to become the UK's first (and, so far only) president of the European Commission, only one Labour person was&nbsp;present along with an Astor, a Rothschild, a Bonham Carter and the chairman of the Royal Opera House. The only link to the great Labour victory of 1945 (when Jenkins first stood for parliament) was the vintage of the wine (Chateau Lafite) and the port (Quinta do Noval).</p><p>There are few better examples of genuine social mobility than this son and grandson of Welsh miners who became not just one of the most formidable politicians of his or any other era, but a writer whose books may well be read long after his considerable political achievements are forgotten. Jenkins was an apple who fell a fair distance from the tree.</p><p>Despite having what we would today describe as a \"back story\" worth flaunting in the inverted aristocracy of the Labour party, Jenkins resolutely refused to use it for political advantage. For some this suggested that he was ashamed of his origins; that his air of <em>de&nbsp;haut en bas</em> was a deliberate attempt to&nbsp;escape his past. But Jenkins would have considered the romantic notion that he dragged himself from the coal face to the dispatch box as fraudulent.</p><p>It was his father, Arthur Jenkins, who had navigated that route. Some readers of this marvellous biography by John Campbell will come away with mixed feelings about Jenkins junior, but few will fail to admire his father; the coal worker who took full advantage of the educational opportunities offered by his union for \"self-improvement\". Arthur was proud to say he went to Oxford but it was to Ruskin College on a scholarship rather than Balliol, where his son went to study PPE (it was a path to a political career even then).</p><p>By the time Arthur and Hattie Jenkins's only child was born in 1920 Arthur was a full-time union official on a middle-class income. Their house was away from the pit villages, with a live-in maid and a head teacher for a neighbour. Campbell describes Arthur Jenkins as \"gentle, bookish, internationalist and resolutely un-militant\". His imprisonment during the general strike was a miscarriage of justice; the nine-month sentence was soon reduced to a few weeks because of public outrage. Young Roy was told that his father was on a union visit to Germany and was bemused by the brass band and cheering crowds that welcomed him back.</p><p>By the time Roy was 14 Arthur had been elected as Labour MP for Pontypool. For seven years, during the war and beyond, he served as Attlee's parliamentary private secretary before a brief period as a junior minister. So Jenkins's childhood resembled Tony Benn's more than it resembled Nye Bevan's.</p><p>What is perhaps surprising is not Jenkins's admirable refusal to play on what his followers saw as impeccable socialist roots, but his complete lack of interest in the trade-union movement, or indeed in workers' education, given how important they'd both been to his father's advancement.</p><p>Perhaps this was an aspect of the elitism he was consistently accused of. More likely he agreed with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/donald-sassoon\" title=\"\">Donald Sassoon</a>'s observation that socialists got rid of a utopian albatross when they \"abandoned the idea that a single class – the traditional male factory-based proletariat – was somehow endowed by history with the task of embodying the hope and aspiration of&nbsp;the whole of humanity\". Jenkins seems to have destroyed this albatross a little sooner than most on the left.</p><p>At the time he was seeking to climb the greasy pole, courting popularity with the unions was essential to success in the Labour party. Instead the young Welsh Gaitskellite soon earned a reputation as a gourmandising dilettante. Roy certainly enjoyed his wine (although he had an aversion to vin blanc and his passion for vin rouge was mainly confined to fine claret). Campbell doesn't attempt an assessment of his subject's daily alcohol intake (as Jenkins did in <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/oct/13/biography.highereducation\" title=\"\">his biography of Churchill</a>) but David Steel records his amazement at how much his great ally could drink at lunch, yet remain unaffected. Throughout his entire political career Jenkins set aside at least an hour and a half every day for a proper lunch with somebody he considered important and convivial. The concept of grabbing a quick sandwich was as alien to him as helping with the housework. As Campbell points out, his subject led an extraordinarily pampered life and if he had a great deal of time to read and write \"it was because there was literally nothing else he was required to do except eat, drink and talk\". Jennifer, his wife of almost 60 years, was amazingly tolerant of this and his other peccadillos.</p><p>The sexual revelations in this book have understandably attracted all the pre-publication publicity. Campbell, however, sets out masterfully the full&nbsp;range of Jenkins's achievements. Considering that he was in parliament for 16 years before his first ministerial appointment he packed an awful lot into his eight years of red boxes and ministerial cars.</p><p>He had the audacity to refuse Wilson's first offer of a cabinet post at&nbsp;education, but the gamble paid off; he&nbsp;was made home secretary instead. Education went to his close friend from Balliol, Tony Crosland. In his autobiography Denis Healey described them as being as close as <a href=\"http://ancienthistory.about.com/library/bl/bl_dioscuri.htm\" title=\"\">Castor and Pollux</a>, but, as Campbell reveals, they were actually much closer.</p><p>A decade later, Crosland was made foreign secretary in the Callaghan government, the job that Jenkins longed for. He decided reluctantly to leave Westminster for Brussels, only to hear of Crosland's premature death six months later. Had he stayed he would almost certainly have succeeded his old buddy.</p><p>That Jenkins and Crosland had a gay relationship at Oxford is extraordinary for two reasons. First, it is revealing that the man who used his first spell as home secretary so effectively to legalise homosexuality had actually committed the illegal offence himself. Second, Jenkins was not only heterosexual from the time he met Jennifer, he was polyamorous (a very Jenkinsonian word) throughout their marriage. Campbell lists the string of lovers who were also family friends. Jenkins would never have an affair with a woman who didn't get on with Jennifer. It was all very French. Crosland, too, took his heterosexuality seriously. After many&nbsp;lovers he married the American journalist Susan Barnes. It's said that he insisted that space in his ministerial diary be preserved for \"conjugal rights\".</p><p>Campbell's portrait belies the view of Jenkins as a lazy hedonist. He certainly didn't fit Healey's depiction of him as Dickens's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/sep/23/charles-dickens-favourite-mutual-friend\" title=\"\">Mr Podsnap</a>. It's true that he had a mannered speaking style, forged in the debating chamber of the Oxford Union: one hand in jacket pocket, the other twisting and writhing in front of him like a snake, as one of his colleagues observed. (A senior Labour figure who knew him well once told me it was as if&nbsp;he were standing behind a buxom wench gently cupping her breast.)</p><p>He was also an extremely shy man but, reading this book, nobody could doubt his diligence or indeed his courage. When he went to defend his cabinet colleague Reg Prentice who was under threat of de-selection in Newham, extremists of right and left hijacked the&nbsp;meeting and turned it into a brawl. Jenkins was hit full on by a flour bomb thrown by a National Front thug. He refused to allow the police to be called and made a rousing speech looking like one of the Homepride men.</p><p>Few politicians can match Jenkins's achievements. In two periods as home secretary he pursued the cause of \"equal opportunity accompanied by cultural diversity in an atmosphere of mutual tolerance\" that he saw as essential to civilised living and social cohesion. As chancellor he \"righted the ship\" after Callaghan's devaluation and as deputy leader he remained consistent in his vision for Britain in Europe when his senior colleagues were performing screeching U-turns. In leading a rebellion by 79 Labour MPs he ensured an emphatic pro-European majority of 112 in a crucial parliamentary debate in October 1971.</p><p>By helping to create the SDP Jenkins believed he saved the Labour party from the Bennite madness of the early 80s. Others (including me) believe he should have stayed to fight alongside those who were determined to save Labour from the clutches of what Attlee once described as \"doctrinaire impossibleism\".</p><p>Had he stayed he would never have&nbsp;been leader, as he was of the SDP. He&nbsp;struggled in the world of 24-hour media and was too shy to go back-slapping. Neither would he have been&nbsp;–&nbsp;as he was following the 1982 byelection – the rather incongruous MP&nbsp;for Glasgow Hillhead (when asked if he&nbsp;would live in the constituency, he calmly explained that while he already owned two houses he would certainly consider acquiring a \"wesidency\" in the city). But he would, I am sure, have accelerated the process of reform and renewal that led to Labour becoming electable again.</p><p>The highest praise I can give to John Campbell's biography is that Roy Jenkins would have been proud to have been its author.</p><p>• Alan Johnson MP is a former home secretary. His memoir<em>,</em> <a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9780552167017\" title=\"\"><em>This Boy</em></a>, is out in paperback from Corgi.</p>","headline":"Roy Jenkins: A Well-Rounded Life – review","trailText":"<strong>Alan Johnson</strong> on the achievements, sex life and 'elitism' of a political heavyweight","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/18/1395162201911/Roy-Jenkins-004.jpg","wordcount":"1520","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-05-02T15:59:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/19/roy-jenkins-well-rounded-life-alan-johnson-review","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/19/roy-jenkins-well-rounded-life-alan-johnson-review","tags":[{"id":"books/politics","webTitle":"Politics","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"h