eated as one.</p><p>This means that any criticism is mildly muted, and the significance of&nbsp;its position in the Banksian oeuvre enhanced. This is fair enough, honourable and decent even; but it's still a novel, and readers still want to know what to expect.</p><p>You can expect much of what Banks has delivered before, but with added rage. Guy, in acute pain and distress at the humiliations visited upon him by his disease, rants against the dying of the light, and is very far indeed from being a noble sufferer. (It is a critical no-no among sophisticates to say \"I&nbsp;didn't like the character[s]\", but frankly, a little of Guy goes a long way, and there's a lot of him here.) The narrative voice – belonging to Kit, Guy's son – is a pleasant relief from this, if a familiar trope: Kit is well up there on the Asperger's spectrum, although the condition is only named once, and then in semi-dismissive passing. Basically, it's a literary device allowing us to look at things closely but entertainingly askew.</p><p>I've been reading Banks's work, on and off, since <em>The Wasp Factory</em> came out. Barely out of my teens then, I was at the ideal age to enjoy the book, and I&nbsp;did. At the time, there was some exciting controversy about it, with questions as to whether this was the literary equivalent of the \"video nasty\" (a phrase much in use then): a work of no artistic merit, designed to shock.</p><p>Still, in place even in his first novel were plenty of the elements that recurred throughout the next three decades, and are all present here: an unbalanced but charismatic father figure; a long-anticipated meeting of interested parties at the isolated locus of the narrative; a secret to be uncovered. And you can add the narrative voice itself: that oddly detached but highly observant tone with a special delight in&nbsp;improvised contraptions, or certain physical phenomena (in this book we&nbsp;get a pleasant and informative digression on laminar flow, the kind that makes the water from a tap running at just the right speed appear motionless. I have a weakness for this kind of thing.)</p><p>And there's the same old nagging question: is this actually a good book? This may cause a collective gasp of outrage from Banks's legions of fans, but then I would say that the reasons I have trouble with some aspects of Banks's writing are the very reasons why he has legions of fans in the first place; and these can be summarised as guilelessness, and the lack of a gap between idea and expression. It's not quite artlessness, more like a lack of cunning literary artifice. Banks's attention is all in the nuts and bolts of construction, and his characters, once established, never surprise, except in unsurprising ways.</p><p>So the people assembling at Guy's house – condemned to be eaten up by the quarry it abuts – are: a film critic of&nbsp;pronounced leftwing leanings; an opportunistic lawyer set to become a New Labour drop-in candidate; a couple of speakers of corporate gobbledegook; a sponging, useless hippy. All revolve around Guy, after their university days&nbsp;together in the 1990s. Guy rants, monotonously if understandably, against the state of the world and his illness; and everyone fulfils their roles,&nbsp;with a lost videotape being the MacGuffin they have all turned up to find. The main problem with all this is the conversation among the characters, which is, to my mind mistakenly, too close to actual speech to be in any way pleasurable to read. Even an idiot in a novel should be an entertaining idiot.</p><p>And yet, like all Banks's fiction that I&nbsp;have read, there is an underlying charm, almost a kind of innocence in the whole set-up and execution. For all&nbsp;its dark resonances, both deliberate and undeliberate, and the true, deep sadness behind the circumstances of its composition, there is something so damned likable about it all. Which is, I&nbsp;hasten to add, a good thing.</p>","headline":"The Quarry by Iain Banks review – a rant against the dying of the light","trailText":"<p><strong>Nicholas Lezard's paperback of the week: </strong>For all its dark resonances and the sadness behind the circumstances of its composition, there is something so damned likable about Banks's last book</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/17/1395061595467/Iain-Banks-006.jpg","wordcount":"702","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-05-02T11:46:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/18/quarry-iain-banks-review-nicholas-lezard","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/18/quarry-iain-banks-review-nicholas-lezard","tags":[{"id":"books/series/nicholas-lezard-choice","webTitle":"Nicholas Lezard's choice","type":"series","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/series/nicholas-lezard-choice","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/series/nicholas-lezard-choice","references":[]},{"id":"books/iainbanks","webTitle":"Iain Banks","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/iainbanks","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/iainbanks","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","references":[]},{"id":"profile/nicholaslezard","webTitle":"Nicholas Lezard","rcsId":"GNL034660","r2ContributorId":"16172","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/7/19/1374241286766/Nicholas-Lezard.jpg","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Nicholas Lezard is a lite