ion from the 16th century to the 1930s is set to go up for auction later this month.</p><p>Running to 1,500 books, including the luridly titled Victorian books Slave-catching in the Indian Ocean, Man-hunting in the Desert and Tramps in Dark Mongolia – not to mention the forgotten histories of British explorers such as John Franklin, who died with 129 crew members searching for the north-west passage in 1845 – the collection has been compiled over the past 45 years by Franklin Brooke-Hitching.</p><p>Sotheby's described it as \"the most magnificent collection of books charting the discovery of the world ever to emerge on the market\", and predicted it would fetch more than £5m. Highlights include a book containing specimens of cloth collected by James Cook in the Pacific, and Ernest Shackleton's Aurora Australis, \"printed at the sign of the Penguins\", the winter quarters of the British Antarctic expedition, in 1909. Members of the expedition took a printing press with them to stave off boredom during the perpetual dark of the Antarctic winter; the books were bound in wooden boards from food provision crates, while spines were made from leather horse harnesses. It is estimated that Brooke-Hitching's example, made from a tea chest and one of about 100 printed, will fetch up to £40,000.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-432507398'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Arts/Arts_/Pictures/2014/3/19/1395247948479/Daniel-Beeckman-orangutan-009.jpg' alt='Daniel Beeckman orangutan illustration' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>An Indonesian orang-utan … from Daniel Beeckman's account of his trip to Borneo. Photograph: Sotheby's</figcaption></figure><p>The collection, which will be sold in a series of four auctions starting on 27 March, also features first editions by Francis Drake, Walter Raleigh, Cook, Darwin, Scott and Shackleton, as well as the 1772 chart of the Pacific Ocean commissioned by botanist Joseph Banks. The chart, known as the earliest printed map of Australia, is one of only three known to have survived.</p><p>\"This sale represents an opportunity for collectors which may never be repeated,\" said Roger Griffiths, head of Sotheby's books and manuscripts department. \"Over 40 years, Franklin Brooke-Hitching has assembled the finest private collection of books relating to exploration and discovery.\"</p><p>Covering stories of exploration from Sir Humphrey Gilbert, the Elizabethan courtier who in 1583 tried to establish the first colony in the New World, to Daniel Beeckman, who in the early 18th century became the first European to discover orangutans in Borneo, the collection delves into \"all corners of the globe\", said Sotheby's.</p><p>With an estimated worth of £10-15,000, the first book printed in Alaska is also included, the Polar Almanac for the Year of our Lord 1854. It was produced on board the HMS Enterprise while anchored in Camden Bay, as it searched for Franklin and the doomed crew of HMS Terror.</p><p>\"Together they tell the story of mankind's persistent quest – over half a millennium – to discover, explore and understand the world. Many of the books are unique or very rare presentation copies from the authors, or in fine bindings, and all are notable for being in the finest condition imaginable,\" said Griffiths.</p>","headline":"Sotheby's to auction unique collection charting history of British exploration","trailText":"<p>Private library including first editions by Drake, Raleigh and other discoverers expected to go under hammer for over £5m</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Arts/Arts_/Pictures/2014/3/19/1395247941846/Daniel-Beeckman-orangutan-004.jpg","wordcount":"490","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-26T15:40:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/20/sothebys-auction-british-exploration-books-drake-raleigh-franklin-brooke-hitching","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/20/sothebys-auction-